<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/2545254-angela"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1454958916i/2545254._UX100_CR0,16,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/2545254-angela">Angela</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    I clicked the spoiler alert box but I fear it isn't showing up so..........<br /><br />SPOILER ALERT. STOP READING IF YOU HAVEN'T READ THE BOOK.<br /><br /><br /><br />I think that in th<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    I clicked the spoiler alert box but I fear it isn't showing up so..........<br /><br />SPOILER ALERT. STOP READING IF YOU HAVEN'T READ THE BOOK.<br /><br /><br /><br />I think that in the beginning after Finn dies, June sees herself as a lone wolf who feels disconnected from all of the people in her life and that Finn was the only one who saw her and understood her. But wolves are pack animals and they are meant to depend on one another for survival. I believe it was Finn who brought June and Toby, another lone wolf, together to show them they need one another. In this same way, through the portrait painting, Finn strengthened not only Greta and June's relationship but the entire network of their family. In the end, I believe they all felt bonded together, almost like a pack of wolves. <br /><br />A few times, wolves were used in the book to describe something scary or vicious and it made me think about the ugly parts of ourselves. Despite the ugliness - Greta's cruel jealousy, Danni's bitter resentment towards Toby and her brother's death, and June's feelings of selfishness and self-loathing, they realize their need for one another and their innate love for one another. This was especially poignant at the end when the man from the Whitney comes to look at the painting and together, like a wolf pack, felt united in some way in defending their family. <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
